3.
    a.
        C
    b.
        A
    c.
        Fluorine is more reactive than Chlorine, because chlorine has a larger atomic radius, so the force with which it attracts electrons from other atoms/molecules to form a chloride ion is lower than the force which fluorine can exert to form fluoride, as the positively charged nucleus of fluorine can be closer to the other molecule's electrons, and the electrostatically attractive force is not shielded by the other electrons. Fluorine and Chlorine have similar chemical properties, however, since they both have seven electrons in their valence shell.
    d.
        i.
            Li + Cl -> LiCl
        ii.
            Test for chloride:
                - add nitric acid
                - add silver nitrate
                - white precipitate, which dissolves in dilute ammonia solution
            Test for Lithium:
                - flame Test
                - use platinum wire
                - dip in hydrochloric acid to clean and then put in flame
                - dip in acid again
                - pick up sample of formed substance with wire
                - put in flame
                - if it is lithium, the flame turns reading
            
            if both tests return positive results, then the product is likely Lithium Chloride.
